        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer66946756" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17803762695890680290">Shadows of the Heart started off with a lack of intensity but once the story line developed the pages began to flow. I was intrigued with the different aspects of the bible he placed in the book. The whole concept was original with the main character being a angel. It described somethings in revelations and the ending of the world. But not in a scary sense. The romance between the characters were genuine. I was on the edge of my seat wondering what would happen as the story climaxed. Although it</span>
  <span id="freeText17803762695890680290" style="display:none">Shadows of the Heart started off with a lack of intensity but once the story line developed the pages began to flow. I was intrigued with the different aspects of the bible he placed in the book. The whole concept was original with the main character being a angel. It described somethings in revelations and the ending of the world. But not in a scary sense. The romance between the characters were genuine. I was on the edge of my seat wondering what would happen as the story climaxed. Although it wasn't my typical genre I would pick up, I would consider reading another one of his works. I think it was a okay start for Lord Williams<br /><br />Dee Jamison<br />AAMBC Reviewer</span>
